    "summary": "The Vijayanagara Empire (1336–1646 AD) was the last great Hindu empire of South India, founded by two brothers Harihara and Bukka Raya — allegedly former ministers of the [[event:2253|Delhi Sultanate]] who converted back to Hinduism — as a deliberate Hindu counterweight to the expanding Islamic states of the Deccan. Located at a naturally fortified site on the Tungabhadra River in modern Karnataka, the capital Hampi became one of the largest cities in the world in the 15th century, with an estimated population of 500,000–1,000,000 and a fame for wealth that astonished visiting traders from Arabia, Portugal, and Persia.\n\nVijayanagara's peak under Krishnadevaraya (reigned 1509–1529) combined military dominance over the rival Deccan Sultanates with extraordinary cultural patronage — he was himself a poet in Telugu and Sanskrit, and his court attracted scholars, poets, and artists from across South India. The empire preserved and patronized the Carnatic classical music tradition, Bharatanatyam dance, and the temple-building traditions of South Indian Hinduism, constructing elaborate temple complexes at Hampi whose ruins (now a UNESCO World Heritage Site) remain among the most spectacular archaeological sites in Asia. Vijayanagara fell at the catastrophic Battle of Talikota (1565), when a coalition of four Deccan Sultanates defeated the imperial army, killing the emperor and sacking Hampi in a destruction so complete that the city — the sixth largest in the world only decades before — was never reoccupied. The ruins at Hampi stretch over 26 square kilometers.",
